            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 4,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1729181984,
            "creation_date": 1579206472,
            "body": "<p>For those who came here looking for a solution to generate <code>java.sql.Timestamp<\/code> instances with better than millisecond precision (the <code>Timestamp<\/code> constructor that accepts nanos is deprecated):<\/p>\n<p><code>Timestamp timestamp = Timestamp.from(Instant.now());<\/code><\/p>\n<p>This assumes your operating system supports better than millisecond precision for the system clock.  It's useful for databases that support better-than-millisecond TIMESTAMP precision, such as with PostgreSQL, which supports microsecond precision.<\/p>\n<p>You can convert it back to an <code>Instant<\/code> or <code>LocalDateTime<\/code>:<\/p>\n<p><code>System.out.println(timestamp.toInstant()); // UTC<\/code><\/p>\n<p>or<\/p>\n<p><code>System.out.println(timestamp.toLocalDateTime()); // local time<\/code><\/p>\n<p>I will also reiterate information stoetti provided in a comment, that according to the documentation link that stoetti provided,\n<a href=\"https://jdbc.postgresql.org/documentation/query/#using-java-8-date-and-time-classes\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">https://jdbc.postgresql.org/documentation/query/#using-java-8-date-and-time-classes<\/a>, the PostgreSQL JDBC driver does recognize the following <code>java.time<\/code> classes as timestamps:<\/p>\n<p><code>java.time.LocalTime<\/code> as <code>TIME [ WITHOUT TIMEZONE ]<\/code><\/p>\n<p><code>java.time.LocalDateTime<\/code> as <code>TIMESTAMP [ WITHOUT TIMEZONE ]<\/code><\/p>\n<p><code>java.time.OffsetDateTime<\/code> as <code>TIMESTAMP WITH TIMEZONE<\/code><\/p>\n<p>But not <code>java.time.Instant<\/code>, as stoetti pointed out.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 59777332,
            "question_id": 59404071,
            "last_edit_date": 1729181984
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5c09f46f4edab31c43465b9f36638678?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 25822,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 66686,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/66686/jens-schauder",
                "reputation": 82662,
                "display_name": "Jens Schauder",
                "accept_rate": 87
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1576736708,
            "creation_date": 1576736708,
            "body": "<p>Spring Data JDBC has no knowledge of the type expected by the SQL-statement. Therefore it passes parameters a long without any conversion and relies on the database to properly handle the parameter.<\/p>\n\n<p>One might argue that it should convert parameters if a matching converter is registered, but this is currently not the case. <\/p>\n\n<p>Therefore currently the solution is to convert the argument yourself and changing the argument type to <code>java.util.Date<\/code> or whatever your JDBC driver is accepting.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 59404260,
            "question_id": 59404071
        }
    ],
